  "answer": "Both couplets were found in the corpus.\n\n**Ghalib** (Diwan-e-Ghalib, chapter 70 — \"Hazaaron khwahishein aisi ke har khwahish pe dam nikle\"):\n\nMatla (transliteration):\n> Hazaaron khwahishein aisi ke har khwahish pe dam nikle\n> Bohat nikle mere armaan lekin phir bhi kam nikle\n\nTranslation:\n> A thousand wishes, each could make my spirit cease;\n> So many of my dreams came true, yet brought so little peace.\n\n**Iqbal** (Bang-e-Dara Part 1, chapter 12 — \"Tere ishq ki inteha chahta hoon\"):\n\nOpening couplet (transliteration):\n> Tere ishq ki inteha chahta hoon\n> Meri saadgi dekh kya chahta hoon\n\nTranslation:\n> The final reach of Your Love is what I seek;\n> Behold my simplicity, what I beseech is what I seek.\n\n---\n\n**How their desire-cosmologies differ:**\n\nGhalib's cosmology is structured by **plurality and fatal expenditure**. The opening image — \"hazaaron\" (thousands) of desires, each causing \"dam nikle\" (breath to depart / soul to exit) — imagines desire as an unending hemorrhage of life itself. Each wish bleeds the self. Crucially, fulfillment doesn't redeem this: \"bohat nikle mere armaan lekin phir bhi kam nikle\" — many longings were satisfied, yet they remained insufficient. The cosmos is structured so that desire can never resolve into fullness. The self is subject to desires; it does not choose them. It is scattered across thousands of objects, each fatal, none sufficient. This is a tragic-horizontal cosmology: the self spread across infinite lacks, spending its breath on each.\n\nIqbal's cosmology is structured by **singularity and willed intensification**. Rather than thousands of desires, Iqbal names one: the \"inteha\" (extreme limit, ultimate reach) of divine love. \"Meri saadgi dekh\" — \"behold my simplicity\" — is both self-deprecating and audacious: he knows that wanting the very limit of divine love is either naive or the most radical act possible. Where Ghalib's self is *consumed by* desire without consent, Iqbal's self *leans into* desire deliberately, seeking not relief but the furthest edge. The later couplets confirm the logic: he wants to hear \"Lan Tarani\" (\"You shall not see Me\" — God's answer to Moses), he wants to be extinguished like a dawn lamp. But these are chosen, purposive extinctions — desire as theological wager, not cosmological fate.\n\nThe decisive contrast: in Ghalib, annihilation is the *byproduct* of desire — each wish kills a little; in Iqbal, annihilation is the *goal* of desire — push love to its limit and be consumed by that limit willingly. Ghalib's self is eroded by the plural; Iqbal's self is intensified toward the singular until it breaks. Ghalib mourns that desire never satisfies; Iqbal insists satisfaction is not the point — total exposure to the divine is.",
